data.content:
Yes — the cast will throw `InvalidCastException` on failure, not return `null`, so `IsNotNull` isn't really testing what you think. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

`IsInstanceOfType<T>` gives a clear failure message (expected vs actual type) instead of an opaque cast exception. If you're on an older MSTest version without the generic overload, use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`.
